                  <additions>
                  <list>
                    <item xml:id="a1">
                    <locus target="#iiv(erso)"/>
                    <desc>
                    Calendar of the Apostles and Evangelists, and some other holidays. At the top is a note which says: The painter of this illumination is Wäldä Mika’el
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a2">
                    <locus target="#160r #160v"/>
                    <desc type="Asmat">
                    Asmat prayer against hail, ጸሎተ፡ በረድ፡.
                    Incipit: <foreign xml:lang="gez">ጸሎተ: በረድ: ደፍፍልዮን: ለአፌን: ጡጠርዮን: ቀራድድዮን: ድልጣኂን:<gap reason="omitted"/>አመሐልኩከ: አማኅፀንኩከ: አንተ: መልአከ: በረድ: ሞርሬዎን: ከመ: ኢታውርድ: በረድ: እምሰማይ:<gap reason="omitted"/></foreign>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a3">
                    <locus target="#176v #177r"> f. 176v, 177r, top margin</locus>
                    <desc type="Asmat">
                    Asmat prayer against physical and spiritual disease, in a later, crude hand
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a4">
                    <locus target="#178r"> f. 178r, column 2 and bottom</locus>
                    <desc type="Asmat">
                    Asmat prayer for spiritual release from chains, in a later hand
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e1">
                    <locus target="#ir(ecto) #iv(erso) #iir(ecto) #179r #179v"/>
                    <desc>
                    blank
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a5">
                    <locus target="#2r #2v #3v #4r #5r"/>
                    <desc>
                    At the beginning of some psalms there is a healing prescription added in a later hand. E.g., F. 1a “Oracle for pregnancy; ‘the leaf does not wither;’” “For enemy, [recite] ‘why do the nations rage?’”, f. 2r “For enemies, [recite] ‘How my enemies multiply’”; f. 2v “When I call, ‘your enemies will scatter;’” 3v “‘O Lord, in your anger’ recite with wine and with vineger and with oil;” f. 4r “if a woman is hated by her husband, anoint her organs with oil and recite;” f. 5r “recite for the love of the people, and anoint with oil.” Veronika Six (“A Psalter from Tübingen: Although Inconspicuous the Text, Neverthless a Treasure for Manuscriptology,” Aethiopica 13 [2010] 163–75), describes this phenomenon in a Psalter in the University of Tübingen; and see the comments in Bogdan Burtea’s entry on “Magic Literature” in EA (III:638–40)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e2">
                    <locus target="#70r"/>
                    <desc>
                    A small red and black cross is written in the margin to mark the midpoint of the <title type="complete" ref="LIT2000Mazmur"/>
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e3">
                    <locus target="#8 #16 #53 #63 #76 #85 #92 #107 #130"/>
                    <desc>
                    red yarn is sewn into the fore edge to mark content as navigation system;
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e4">
                    <desc>
                    Numbered quires: quires 1–16
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="a6">
                    <desc>
                    Psalm 118 does not contain the spiritual meanings of the Hebrew letters
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e5">
                    <locus target="#7v #11r #43v #46r #47r"/>
                    <desc>
                    (etc.) words of text are written interlinearly;
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e6">
                    <locus target="#28r #54r #88r #88v #107v"/>
                    <desc>
                    (etc.) lines of text are written interlinearly;
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e7">
                    <locus target="#15v #22r #23v #26v"/>
                    <desc>
                    (etc.) text has been removed
                    </desc>
                    </item>
                    <item xml:id="e8">
                    <desc>
                    The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the scribe reduces the font size at the end of lines to avoid having to go onto the next line (throughout)
                    </desc>
                    </item>
